assessment_details.task_description:
Throughout the semester students will learn about research design, implementation and analysis. Students will be allocated into groups of approximatley 3-4 students for this assessment task. Students are to identify a research problem or gap in knowledge and develop a detailed research proposal to address this research problem or gap in knowledge. The research proposal should comprise no more than 3,500 words (excluding appendices) and should include:

brief background to the research problem and how it fits with previous studies and literature;

project aims, research questions, objectives and/or hypotheses;

significance or importance of the proposed research academically or for practice/policy (the so what question);

research philosophy, design, sampling and proposed data collection methods;

potential research validity and reliability issues as well as limitations;

proposed data analysis techniques to be employed and how the data may be presented;

research timeline and budget;

appendices (including instruments such as personal interview sheets, draft surveys etc).

<p> It is expected that the report will integrate and use key concepts and material from the course to support and justify the details outlined in the proposal. In particular, the proposal will need to integrate and use research method texts in the report to justfy decisions and should ensure a link between the research design, implementation and analysis. The proposal should be written in a structured format and can use bullet points. The proposal itself should be detailed enough for a researcher to successfully implement the proposal and collect data.<p>

Students are also expected to complete a group peer assessment sheet and provide this to the course convenor with the report. This form will detail the contribution of each group member to the group report. Marks may be allocated based on the level of student input into the group report. <p>
Further information on the assessment task and peer assessment form can be found on the Blackboard site and will be discussed in class.
